The Sunfish, also known as Mola mola, is a large and oddly shaped fish that belongs to the family Molidae. It can be found in temperate and tropical waters around the world.

The sunfish is easily recognizable by its unique appearance. Its body is laterally compressed, meaning it's extremely flat from side to side like a pancake or frisbee. The body shape may range from an almost perfect circle to a more elongated oval form. They have small pectoral fins on the sides of their bodies and tiny anal fins near their tails.

Sunfish can grow quite large â€“ some adult specimens reach over 10 feet (3 meters) in length and weigh about 2 tons (4,409 pounds). Their skin color ranges from silver-gray to dark blue or blackish on top with white undersides. Some sunfish have lighter patterns toward their dorsal fin areas.
